03:01.529 --> 03:04.488
- Grab a sheet, will you?
- EMS just dropped off.

03:04.532 --> 03:06.229
♪

03:06.273 --> 03:07.709
[radio chatter]

03:07.752 --> 03:09.798
♪

03:09.841 --> 03:11.713
Wait.
- What?

03:11.756 --> 03:13.193
- Do you hear that?

03:13.236 --> 03:14.846
- Hear what?

03:16.631 --> 03:18.328
Doctor Bloom, she's dead.

03:18.372 --> 03:20.722
No pulse, no BP,
cyanotic, rigor mortis.

03:20.765 --> 03:22.898
- I need a defib ventilator,
ALS,

03:22.941 --> 03:24.595
and resuscitation team, now!

03:24.639 --> 03:25.944
- That's impossible,
she's dead.

03:25.988 --> 03:28.730
- Well, at least you didn't
kill her twice.

03:28.773 --> 03:30.558
- New Amsterdam
has a public school,

03:30.601 --> 03:32.995
prison ward,
and facilities for the UN.

03:33.038 --> 03:34.866
We performed the world's
first C-section

03:34.910 --> 03:36.607
in the world's first
maternity ward.

03:36.651 --> 03:39.306
New Amsterdam is America's
first public hospital.

03:39.349 --> 03:41.264
Patients don't need insurance,
money...

03:41.308 --> 03:43.527
- Dora, I know the history.
- The dean makes me tell it

03:43.571 --> 03:45.312
to every new medical director.

03:45.355 --> 03:47.009
- And how many of those
have you worked with?

03:47.052 --> 03:49.925
- Five in five years.

03:49.968 --> 03:51.709
- Dr. Helen Sharpe.

03:51.753 --> 03:54.234
Max Goodwin, how can I help?
- Oh, you're too kind.

03:54.277 --> 03:55.713
Welcome to The Dam.

03:55.757 --> 03:57.889
Why are you in scrubs?
- Because I'm a doctor.

03:57.933 --> 03:59.848
Going somewhere?
- I have to tape segments

03:59.891 --> 04:01.763
with "The Morning Show"
and Megyn Kelly,

04:01.806 --> 04:03.765
then give the keynote address
at the oncology conference

04:03.808 --> 04:05.419
in Vail.
- I'll take that for you.

04:05.462 --> 04:06.898
- Thank you.
- Wow, you're gonna do all that

04:06.942 --> 04:08.465
on your lunch break.
- [laughs]

04:08.509 --> 04:10.250
You're funny.
I'll be back next week.

04:10.293 --> 04:12.513
We'll lunch at the Tavern--
my treat.

04:12.556 --> 04:14.428
- Unlike the previous
medical director,

04:14.471 --> 04:16.604
I actually expect you
to practice medicine

04:16.647 --> 04:18.780
at this hospital because...

04:18.823 --> 04:21.609
I don't know, it's your job.

04:22.827 --> 04:24.568
- You're funny.

04:24.612 --> 04:26.875
- You said that.

04:26.918 --> 04:29.399
- I'll tell you what.
I'll continue giving speeches

04:29.443 --> 04:31.488
all over the world,
because you can't afford

04:31.532 --> 04:33.925
the kind of publicity
I give this hospital.

04:33.969 --> 04:36.450
And I'll continue
my on-air appearances

04:36.493 --> 04:38.756
with Ellen, Oprah,
and anyone else powerful enough

04:38.800 --> 04:40.671
to go by one name,
because someone has

04:40.715 --> 04:42.934
to remind New York
that even though New Amsterdam

04:42.978 --> 04:44.675
is an under-funded
public hospital,

04:44.719 --> 04:46.764
we can still go toe-to-toe
with the privates

04:46.808 --> 04:49.593
from basic care
to state-of-the-art procedures.

04:49.637 --> 04:50.855
I will be back next week.

04:50.899 --> 04:52.335
We'll lunch at the Tavern.

04:52.379 --> 04:53.989
My treat.

04:54.032 --> 04:57.427
[funky music]

04:57.471 --> 04:59.473
- I like her.

04:59.516 --> 05:01.562
If she comes back,
let's keep her.

05:01.605 --> 05:02.737
♪

05:02.780 --> 05:05.043
[announcements playing
over PA]

05:05.087 --> 05:06.915
[phone line ringing]

05:06.958 --> 05:09.570
[ethereal, thumping music]
[phone ringing]

05:09.613 --> 05:11.963
- [exhales]
Sorry.

05:12.007 --> 05:13.661
♪

05:16.577 --> 05:17.708
[phone beeps]

05:17.752 --> 05:18.970
Max.

05:19.014 --> 05:20.450
Is everything okay?

05:20.494 --> 05:21.973
- Just calling to say hi.

05:22.017 --> 05:23.627
- Really?

05:23.671 --> 05:26.064
- Isn't that what people do?
- People, yeah.

05:26.108 --> 05:27.501
You?

05:27.544 --> 05:29.459
Not so much.

05:29.503 --> 05:30.765
- [laughs]

05:30.808 --> 05:32.984
I'm trying.

05:33.028 --> 05:35.117
- How's the, uh...
- Can I, uh...

05:35.160 --> 05:36.466
- [laughs]

05:36.510 --> 05:37.946
Sorry, what?
- No, you--

05:37.989 --> 05:39.861
- I was...

05:39.904 --> 05:42.429
I was just going to ask
about the apartment.

05:42.472 --> 05:44.474
- Oh, it's great.
Yeah.

05:44.518 --> 05:45.823
You should come by sometime.
Sit on the floor,

05:45.867 --> 05:47.825
eat some soy sauce packets.

05:47.869 --> 05:50.393
Have you had any time...

05:50.437 --> 05:51.742
to think...
- Max.

05:51.786 --> 05:53.744
It's time.

05:53.788 --> 05:55.964
- Um...

05:56.007 --> 05:57.792
Georgia, I have to...
- Save the world?

05:57.835 --> 05:59.533
I know.
Go.

05:59.576 --> 06:01.839
- But listen--listen,
I know what I did was wrong.

06:01.883 --> 06:03.145
I should have
put you and the baby first,

06:03.188 --> 06:05.843
but I am gonna change.

06:05.887 --> 06:08.368
And I'm gonna win you back.

06:08.411 --> 06:10.805
- Well, you have 12 weeks.

06:12.502 --> 06:14.896
[all chattering]

06:18.900 --> 06:21.511
- Hey, Reynolds.
- One second.

06:21.555 --> 06:23.513
Hey.
- I've been thinking about you.

06:23.557 --> 06:25.689
You, uh, wanna
grab a drink later?

06:25.733 --> 06:27.691
- I can't.
- You know when I say

06:27.735 --> 06:29.867
"grab a drink" I don't really
mean "grab a drink."

06:29.911 --> 06:31.739
- I do.

06:37.484 --> 06:40.051
- Sorry.
I'm so sorry.

06:40.095 --> 06:42.402
[rustling]
Sorry.

06:42.445 --> 06:45.448
[grunts]
So sorry.

06:45.492 --> 06:46.971
You guys okay?

06:53.674 --> 06:55.719
- There he is.

06:57.112 --> 06:58.722
- [sighs]

07:02.944 --> 07:04.815
Uh...

07:04.859 --> 07:06.991
my sister Luna and I

07:07.035 --> 07:09.472
were, um, born here

07:09.516 --> 07:10.908
in New Amsterdam.

07:10.952 --> 07:13.911
And then eight years later,

07:13.955 --> 07:15.609
uh...

07:15.652 --> 07:17.698
Luna died here.

07:17.741 --> 07:20.918
It was a hospital-acquired
infection.

07:20.962 --> 07:24.052
Entirely preventable.

07:24.095 --> 07:26.097
So...

07:26.141 --> 07:28.622
working here--
being able to save

07:28.665 --> 07:30.841
someone else's sister

07:30.885 --> 07:33.148
or someone's daughter...

07:34.715 --> 07:37.108
It's a dream come true...

07:37.152 --> 07:38.458
for me.

07:38.501 --> 07:40.460
Anyway, so...

07:40.503 --> 07:42.853
[clears throat]
How can I help?

07:47.162 --> 07:49.512
Uh, sorry.
That's not a trick question.

07:49.556 --> 07:51.775
I'm--I'm really just asking.

07:51.819 --> 07:54.996
I work for you so you can
work for your patients.

07:55.997 --> 07:57.955
How can I help?

07:57.999 --> 08:00.001
Just shout it out.

08:01.263 --> 08:03.613
Really? No one?

08:03.657 --> 08:05.833
Wow.

08:05.876 --> 08:07.748
Okay, why don't we try this:
I'll go first.

08:07.791 --> 08:09.793
Will everyone in the Cardiac
Surgical Department

08:09.837 --> 08:11.621
please raise your hands.

08:11.665 --> 08:13.144
Don't be shy,
just get them up there.

08:13.188 --> 08:14.842
Great.

08:14.885 --> 08:16.234
[indistinct murmuring]

08:16.278 --> 08:17.714
Great, thank you.

08:17.758 --> 08:20.848
You're all fired.
[all gasp, exclaim]

08:20.891 --> 08:23.807
Any department
who places billing above care--

08:23.851 --> 08:26.506
no matter how much money
you make this hospital--

08:26.549 --> 08:27.550
you will be terminated.

08:27.594 --> 08:29.247
Oh, I am serious.

08:29.291 --> 08:31.162
Bye-bye.

08:31.206 --> 08:32.990
[all murmuring]

08:33.034 --> 08:35.253
We're gonna be starting over,
all right?

08:35.297 --> 08:37.560
[line trilling]
Without you.

08:37.604 --> 08:39.214
Sorry.

08:40.650 --> 08:42.696
Next, will all
the department chairs

08:42.739 --> 08:44.915
raise your hands, please.

08:47.178 --> 08:49.746
I have no idea
how you managed

08:49.790 --> 08:52.096
to keep this hospital afloat
with so little help,

08:52.140 --> 08:55.056
so I'm gonna hire you
50 new attendings.

08:55.099 --> 08:56.753
Because untrained residents

08:56.797 --> 08:58.581
will no longer be
running this hospital,

08:58.625 --> 09:00.017
regardless of how much money

09:00.061 --> 09:02.933
their university makes
off their indentured servitude

09:02.977 --> 09:05.022
or how much time
it affords some of you

09:05.066 --> 09:07.111
to play golf.

09:07.155 --> 09:09.679
[angry murmuring]

09:09.723 --> 09:10.941
- [laughing softly]

09:10.985 --> 09:12.639
- So...

09:12.682 --> 09:14.728
let me ask again...

09:16.251 --> 09:18.253
How can I help?

09:20.081 --> 09:21.299
Yeah.

09:21.343 --> 09:22.997
Person not calling
their lawyer.

09:23.040 --> 09:24.999
- Lauren Bloom,
emergency department.

09:25.042 --> 09:27.784
Uh, I want to get rid
of our waiting room.

09:27.828 --> 09:29.090
- Okay, what do you--
where do you want to put it?

09:29.133 --> 09:30.700
- I want to get rid of it.

09:30.744 --> 09:32.572
I want to move patients
direct to bed--

09:32.615 --> 09:34.051
no waiting room.

09:34.095 --> 09:35.749
- Done.

09:35.792 --> 09:36.924
- Really?

09:36.967 --> 09:39.274
- Sure, let's try it.

09:39.317 --> 09:41.711
Yeah.
- Hi--Dr. Iggy Frome,

09:41.755 --> 09:43.147
head of psych.

09:43.191 --> 09:45.759
Can we do something
about healthy food?

09:45.802 --> 09:47.587
- What do you want
to do about it?

09:47.630 --> 09:48.718
- Uh, have some.

09:48.762 --> 09:49.806
[all laughing]

09:49.850 --> 09:51.199
To eat in--in the hospital.

09:51.242 --> 09:53.027
- [laughing]
Okay.

09:53.070 --> 09:54.332
Done.

09:54.376 --> 09:56.073
- Aces.
Thank you.

09:56.117 --> 09:57.684
- Thank you.
- [grunts softly]

09:57.727 --> 09:59.990
You know, we all feel like
the system...

10:00.034 --> 10:01.775
is too big to change,
but guess what?

10:01.818 --> 10:03.603
We are the system.

10:03.646 --> 10:05.256
And we need to change.

10:05.300 --> 10:07.084
So just tell me what you need--
what your patients need--

10:07.128 --> 10:08.651
and I don't care
if it's not covered,

10:08.695 --> 10:10.653
I don't care if the board
said no,

10:10.697 --> 10:11.828
let's get into some trouble.

10:11.872 --> 10:13.264
Let's be...

10:13.308 --> 10:15.266
doctors again.

10:15.310 --> 10:17.051
[spirited music]

10:17.094 --> 10:18.269
Okay, I appreciate it.

10:18.313 --> 10:19.923
Go, and I'll see you
out in the wards.

10:19.967 --> 10:21.664
Thanks.

10:21.708 --> 10:24.101
[all chattering]

10:24.145 --> 10:25.102
♪

10:25.146 --> 10:26.669
Uh, Bloom.

10:26.713 --> 10:29.629
Sorry, could I, uh,
borrow you for a minute?

10:29.672 --> 10:32.240
Um, I need you
to do a throat biopsy.

10:32.283 --> 10:33.937
It'll just take a second.
- Sure.

10:33.981 --> 10:36.766
Uh, for what patient?

10:36.810 --> 10:39.029
- Uh, me.

10:40.857 --> 10:41.031
.

10:41.075 --> 10:43.991
[indistinct chatter]

10:45.688 --> 10:47.821
[announcements playing
over PA]

10:52.739 --> 10:54.697
Yeah, hey, how are you?
- Hello?

10:54.741 --> 10:56.699
My name is Alain.
I wrote my name down.

10:56.743 --> 10:58.570
- Then we'll call you when
we have a doctor available.

10:58.614 --> 10:59.833
Okay, hun?

11:02.792 --> 11:04.533
- At New Amsterdam's
department

11:04.576 --> 11:06.230
of pediatric oncology,
we strive to ensure

11:06.274 --> 11:08.624
that the children feel
that they are in a relaxed,

11:08.668 --> 11:09.886
positive environment...

11:09.930 --> 11:11.105
- You know what,
she is good.

11:11.148 --> 11:13.107
She is.
- How long have you

11:13.150 --> 11:14.674
noticed irritation?
- Do you think she's

11:14.717 --> 11:16.719
coming back early?
- No.

11:16.763 --> 11:18.286
- Max?
- Yeah, four weeks.

11:18.329 --> 11:19.722
Six.
Maybe eight?

11:19.766 --> 11:21.245
I don't know.
You look tired.

11:21.289 --> 11:22.812
Do you need a nap?
- I need you to stay still.

11:22.856 --> 11:24.596
- Mm.
- Good luck with that.

11:24.640 --> 11:25.685
[phone ringing]

11:25.728 --> 11:26.947
- [mumbling]
Who's calling?

11:26.990 --> 11:28.644
- Dean of medicine.
Third time.

11:28.688 --> 11:30.167
- Ignore.
- Max.

11:30.211 --> 11:32.169
Please stop talking.
- Yeah.

11:32.213 --> 11:33.780
Wait, what's on my hot list
after this?

11:33.823 --> 11:35.259
- What's a hot list?
- It's a to-do list,

11:35.303 --> 11:37.131
but, you know, with a--
with a cooler--

11:37.174 --> 11:39.002
cooler name.
- Call the dean back.

11:39.046 --> 11:40.961
- Uh, after that.
- You know, I can

11:41.004 --> 11:42.614
come back later.
- Well, you've got

11:42.658 --> 11:44.704
the entire United Nations
in the ICU,

11:44.747 --> 11:46.749
and a cardiac patient
being prepped for surgery.

11:46.793 --> 11:48.272
- Right--wait,
why is a cardiac surgery

11:48.316 --> 11:50.318
on my hot list?
- Because you fired

11:50.361 --> 11:52.233
all the cardiac surgeons.
- Right, but I had all

11:52.276 --> 11:53.974
the new patients rerouted
to University.

11:54.017 --> 11:55.758
- Not the ones from Rikers.

11:55.802 --> 11:58.239
Maybe you shouldn't have fired
the entire department.

11:58.282 --> 11:59.762
- They were all corrupt
and lazy.

11:59.806 --> 12:01.721
- See?
- Except for Dr. Reynolds.

12:01.764 --> 12:03.287
- How you know that?

12:04.811 --> 12:05.986
- Just read his file.

12:06.029 --> 12:07.727
- Ow.

12:07.770 --> 12:10.033
[indistinct chatter]

12:14.690 --> 12:16.257
- Doctor...

12:16.300 --> 12:18.172
Frome?
- Please sign in

12:18.215 --> 12:19.782
and take a seat.

12:19.826 --> 12:22.219
- Dr. Frome.

12:22.263 --> 12:23.873
- Young lady, it is
way too early in my day

12:23.917 --> 12:26.136
to call security, but I will.
- Dr. Frome!

12:26.180 --> 12:27.747
Dr. Frome!
Dr. Frome!

12:27.790 --> 12:29.009
- Whoa, whoa, whoa!
Hey!

12:29.052 --> 12:30.575
Hey, it's okay!
- Dr. Frome!

12:30.619 --> 12:31.576
I got it.
Jemma, hi, hey.

12:31.620 --> 12:32.926
I got this, thank you.

12:32.969 --> 12:34.188
All right, come on,
come with me.

12:34.231 --> 12:35.798
Thank you.

12:35.842 --> 12:38.801
[somber music]

12:38.845 --> 12:45.895
♪

12:47.201 --> 12:49.856
It's okay, whatever it is.

12:49.899 --> 12:51.771
- It happened...

12:51.814 --> 12:53.642
again.

12:53.685 --> 12:58.212
♪

12:58.255 --> 13:00.605
- Floyd Reynolds?

13:00.649 --> 13:02.259
Max Goodwin.
- Yeah, I remember you

13:02.303 --> 13:04.348
from an hour ago.

13:04.392 --> 13:06.263
When you fired me.

13:06.307 --> 13:07.961
- Yale.
Fancy.

13:08.004 --> 13:10.180
What secret society were you?
Skull and Bones?

13:10.224 --> 13:11.834
Scroll and Key?
- The one that took

13:11.878 --> 13:13.096
a poor black kid.

13:13.140 --> 13:14.837
- Which one was that?

13:14.881 --> 13:16.796
- School of medicine.

13:19.407 --> 13:21.888
- So, Floyd,
why did you become

13:21.931 --> 13:24.020
a cardiovascular surgeon?
- You know, all due respect,

13:24.064 --> 13:26.109
I don't need a pat on the back
on the way out.

13:26.153 --> 13:27.894
- That's good,
because I don't intend

13:27.937 --> 13:29.243
to pat you on the back given
the appalling history

13:29.286 --> 13:30.853
of patient care
in your department.

13:30.897 --> 13:32.159
- If I were you and I had
analyzed our performance

13:32.202 --> 13:33.943
I would have done the same.
- Hmm.

13:33.987 --> 13:35.771
By performance, do you mean
the highest mortality

13:35.815 --> 13:37.947
and infection rates
in New York City?

13:37.991 --> 13:39.949
'Cause that's like the Beyoncé
of performances

13:39.993 --> 13:42.082
if Beyoncé, you know,
killed people.

13:42.125 --> 13:44.171
- Yeah, and don't forget
our rampant culture

13:44.214 --> 13:45.912
of inflating billable hours.

13:45.955 --> 13:47.957
- Except you didn't.

13:49.785 --> 13:50.873
I read your files.
You have the lowest

13:50.917 --> 13:52.092
billing rates
in the department.

13:52.135 --> 13:53.833
What's wrong?
You don't like surgery?

13:53.876 --> 13:55.835
- I love surgery.
- Then why did you perform

13:55.878 --> 13:57.967
half as many procedures
as your colleagues?

13:58.011 --> 14:00.143
- Because my patients
didn't need them.

14:00.187 --> 14:01.797
Because there's other ways
to help people

14:01.841 --> 14:03.277
than my cutting them open.

14:03.320 --> 14:06.280
[mellow music]

14:06.323 --> 14:09.326
♪

14:09.370 --> 14:11.763
- That's a cute kid.
- [laughs]

14:11.807 --> 14:13.765
That's my nephew.

14:13.809 --> 14:15.245
- I'm unfiring you.

14:15.289 --> 14:16.812
♪

14:16.856 --> 14:18.379
- To do what?

14:18.422 --> 14:20.250
- To run the Cardiac
Surgical Department.

14:20.294 --> 14:22.165
- There is no Cardiac
Surgical Department.

14:22.209 --> 14:24.167
- Then build one.

14:24.211 --> 14:27.083
A good one.

14:27.127 --> 14:30.913
I mean, it's only people's
heart's we're talking about.

14:30.957 --> 14:34.395
- You do know the whole
system's rigged, don't you?

14:34.438 --> 14:36.310
I mean, they're not gonna
let you come in here

14:36.353 --> 14:38.486
and just help people.

14:38.529 --> 14:40.314
- So let's help as many
as we can before

14:40.357 --> 14:42.229
they figure us out.

14:42.272 --> 14:43.795
You can't say no.

14:43.839 --> 14:45.710
You already unpacked.

14:45.754 --> 14:51.412
♪

14:52.979 --> 14:54.981
- Jemma first came to me
eight years ago

14:55.024 --> 14:57.157
after she was sexually abused
by her foster father.

14:57.200 --> 14:58.985
- Just tell me how long
before I can place her.

14:59.028 --> 15:00.943
- Two years after that,
she came back

15:00.987 --> 15:02.336
after she was found chained
to a radiator

15:02.379 --> 15:03.946
being fed like a dog.

15:03.990 --> 15:06.470
- How long, Iggy?
- This girl has been abused

15:06.514 --> 15:08.211
three times
in the foster care system,

15:08.255 --> 15:09.430
and you want
to put her right back in?

15:09.473 --> 15:11.867
- What other options
do we have?

15:13.303 --> 15:16.045
[kids chattering]

15:16.089 --> 15:17.525
- I'm keeping her.
- What do you mean,

15:17.568 --> 15:18.961
"keeping her"?
- I mean I'm not

15:19.005 --> 15:20.441
discharging her.
I'm keeping her.

15:20.484 --> 15:23.139
- Until when?
- Until she's 18.

15:23.183 --> 15:25.881
- [scoffs] But that's...
- Two years.

15:25.925 --> 15:27.404
- So you are
committing a patient

15:27.448 --> 15:30.016
just to keep them
out of foster care?

15:30.059 --> 15:31.800
- [sighs]

15:31.843 --> 15:33.933
Yeah.

15:33.976 --> 15:36.936
[funky music]

15:36.979 --> 15:39.242
♪

15:39.286 --> 15:40.852
- Doctor, um...

15:40.896 --> 15:42.506
- Goodwin, but call me Max.

15:42.550 --> 15:44.987
I was just taking an interest.

15:45.031 --> 15:46.989
- Surely you don't have
the time to take an interest

15:47.033 --> 15:49.078
in every single case.
- Well, that's why I wear

15:49.122 --> 15:50.993
my running shoes.

15:51.037 --> 15:53.169
- I've been practicing here
for 25 years,

15:53.213 --> 15:56.216
The key to survival is
to have more than one speed.

15:56.259 --> 15:57.913
- I can go faster.

15:57.957 --> 15:59.349
- That's not what I meant.

15:59.393 --> 16:01.351
- Just keep me in the loop
on this, will you?

16:01.395 --> 16:03.353
Hi.

16:05.355 --> 16:08.010
- [sighs]
Good afternoon, Mr. Martín.

16:08.054 --> 16:10.273
I'm Dr. Vijay Kapoor,
your wife's neurologist.

16:10.317 --> 16:13.102
- What happened to her?
- Let me first find my glasses

16:13.146 --> 16:15.975
so that I can read her chart.
- Eh...

16:17.063 --> 16:18.107
- Oh.
[laughs]

16:18.151 --> 16:19.239
There they are.

16:19.282 --> 16:20.457
Thank you.

16:20.501 --> 16:23.417
Presented cyanotic
and rigor mortis.

16:23.460 --> 16:26.898
Administered Diazepam
and Valium.

16:26.942 --> 16:28.813
So, Mr. Martín...

16:28.857 --> 16:30.990
it appears Patricia's brain
convinced her heart

16:31.033 --> 16:33.470
that she was dead, even though
she was very much alive.

16:33.514 --> 16:35.603
We are going to perform
a few tests

16:35.646 --> 16:37.083
to find out why.

16:37.126 --> 16:38.475
In the mean time,

16:38.519 --> 16:41.609
you and I are going to talk.
- Talk?

16:41.652 --> 16:43.306
- Talk about
your life together,

16:43.350 --> 16:46.048
how you met,
how you live.

16:46.092 --> 16:49.573
- What does that have to do
with what happened to her?

16:49.617 --> 16:52.054
- Everything.

16:52.098 --> 16:54.013
[tense music]

16:54.056 --> 16:55.927
[announcements playing
over PA]

16:55.971 --> 16:59.496
♪

16:59.540 --> 17:02.021
- [breathing heavily]

17:02.064 --> 17:07.983
♪

17:08.027 --> 17:09.463
- Get a resuscitation team.

17:09.506 --> 17:11.552
- Give me a bio.
- Respiration shallow.

17:11.595 --> 17:13.858
- Okay, give me a CBC, BMP,

17:13.902 --> 17:16.035
chem 7, and a saline lock.

17:16.078 --> 17:18.298
Anybody know who this is?
- I found a boarding pass

17:18.341 --> 17:21.040
in his pocket.

17:21.083 --> 17:22.171
- Stop.

17:22.215 --> 17:24.086
Everyone back away
from the patient.

17:24.130 --> 17:25.870
Masks on, now.

17:25.914 --> 17:28.003
[overlapping chatter]

17:28.047 --> 17:30.658
♪

17:30.701 --> 17:33.530
[line trilling]

17:33.574 --> 17:36.098
- This is Max.
- We have a patient in the ED

17:36.142 --> 17:39.362
from Liberia presenting
with all the signs of malaria,

17:39.406 --> 17:41.930
Lassa Fever, TB, or...

17:41.973 --> 17:43.497
- Ebola.

17:43.540 --> 17:47.327
♪

17:50.591 --> 17:50.808
.

17:50.852 --> 17:52.897
[monitor beeping]

17:52.941 --> 17:55.552
- First thing we do is call
the mayor's office

17:55.596 --> 17:58.338
and the CDC if we even suspect
ebola virus.

17:58.381 --> 18:00.862
Now, the patient is
in an isolation chamber

18:00.905 --> 18:02.603
with negative pressure airflow.

18:02.646 --> 18:04.735
That chamber is equipped
with every available medicine

18:04.779 --> 18:07.173
should the patient need
to self medicate.

18:07.216 --> 18:09.566
- What about us?
- Ebola isn't airborne,

18:09.610 --> 18:11.960
but if you develop symptoms
you will join him.

18:12.003 --> 18:13.918
Until then, you will help him.

18:13.962 --> 18:16.007
Everyone interacting
with the patient is required

18:16.051 --> 18:17.879
to wear personal
protective equipment

18:17.922 --> 18:19.228
at all times.

18:19.272 --> 18:21.404
No shortcuts, ever.

18:21.448 --> 18:24.190
[tense music]

18:24.233 --> 18:26.235
Good.

18:26.279 --> 18:27.889
[door hisses]

18:27.932 --> 18:29.717
Once blood is drawn,
the test results will come back

18:29.760 --> 18:31.632
in 24 to 48 hours.

18:31.675 --> 18:33.329
♪

18:33.373 --> 18:35.026
- Commencing a Code Green
blood draw

18:35.070 --> 18:36.724
at 1:10 PM,

18:36.767 --> 18:39.335
New Amsterdam Hospital.

18:39.379 --> 18:42.425
- Your husband said
you are taking Haloperidol.

18:42.469 --> 18:43.818
- For two years.

18:43.861 --> 18:45.559
For depression.

18:45.602 --> 18:48.301
- And last year you were
diagnosed with Parkinson's.

18:48.344 --> 18:50.216
- Does any of it explain

18:50.259 --> 18:52.566
what is happening to me?
- Not yet.

18:52.609 --> 18:54.263
I'm going to run
some more tests,

18:54.307 --> 18:55.743
and hopefully...
- More tests?

18:55.786 --> 18:57.527
But she's in pain, and--

18:57.571 --> 18:59.573
and she's not getting
any better.

18:59.616 --> 19:02.053
- Mr. Martín, I need
some more information

19:02.097 --> 19:03.794
before I can make a diagnosis.

19:03.838 --> 19:05.709
- How can you not
do something for her?

19:05.753 --> 19:06.797
- Shh.

19:06.841 --> 19:08.886
- We are going to do something.

19:08.930 --> 19:11.759
We are going to keep talking.

19:11.802 --> 19:13.891
Where are my glasses?

19:13.935 --> 19:16.285
Okay, thank you.

19:18.635 --> 19:20.768
[both arguing in Russian]

19:20.811 --> 19:22.944
[spirited percussion music]

19:22.987 --> 19:24.772
- Whoa, whoa.

19:24.815 --> 19:26.817
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

19:26.861 --> 19:28.602
What's the problem?

19:28.645 --> 19:31.257
- I demand doctor.
- He wants to be discharged.

19:31.300 --> 19:32.823
Dr. Chen needs him
for observation.

19:32.867 --> 19:34.390
- Mister Ambassador,
I'm Dr. Goodwin.

19:34.434 --> 19:35.783
I am the new
medical director here,

19:35.826 --> 19:37.611
and I am officially
discharging you.

19:37.654 --> 19:39.308
- [sighs]
Thank you.

19:39.352 --> 19:40.831
- Before you go,
can you just translate

19:40.875 --> 19:42.572
one thing for your
security detail?

19:42.616 --> 19:44.008
- [grunts]
What?

19:44.052 --> 19:45.880
- Since you're being
released early and against

19:45.923 --> 19:47.577
the wishes of your doctor,
they should look for any signs

19:47.621 --> 19:49.666
of lethargy, brain damage,
cardiac arrest,

19:49.710 --> 19:51.668
sudden loss of consciousness,
and, of course,

19:51.712 --> 19:53.670
rectal bleeding.

19:56.107 --> 19:58.501
Mister Ambassador?

19:59.720 --> 20:02.288
- Maybe I stay.

20:02.331 --> 20:04.115
[speaking in Russian]

20:05.856 --> 20:07.858
- Can I have our menus back?

20:07.902 --> 20:10.992
♪

20:11.035 --> 20:14.038
[both speaking Spanish]

20:16.737 --> 20:18.304
- Claro.

20:18.347 --> 20:19.870
♪

20:19.914 --> 20:21.655
- Hey.
Welcome back.

20:21.698 --> 20:23.134
I heard you got promoted.

20:23.178 --> 20:24.658
- Right after I got fired.

20:24.701 --> 20:26.660
Lord works in mysterious ways.
- Mm.

20:26.703 --> 20:28.357
She does, doesn't she?

20:28.401 --> 20:30.620
A patient from Rikers
was admitted with 17 lacs.

20:30.664 --> 20:32.405
Ruptured spleen, aortic tear.

20:32.448 --> 20:35.538
We got him stable in the ED,
but the tear is all you.

20:35.582 --> 20:37.366
You, uh, wanna grab
a drink tomorrow?

20:37.410 --> 20:38.759
- I can't.

20:38.802 --> 20:40.456
- You know when I say
"grab a drink"

20:40.500 --> 20:42.371
I don't actually...
- Yes, I do.

20:42.415 --> 20:43.764
- Okay.

20:43.807 --> 20:45.069
Wait, you--

20:45.113 --> 20:47.376
you're not trying to...
- [groans]

20:47.420 --> 20:49.378
Look, Lauren...

20:49.422 --> 20:51.815
I think you're great.
- Oh, wow.

20:51.859 --> 20:53.730
You are trying to.
- Okay, I--

20:53.774 --> 20:55.819
I guess I'd rather us
just be...

20:55.863 --> 20:56.907
friends again.

20:56.951 --> 20:58.866
You know, colleagues.

20:58.909 --> 21:00.650
- But I thought we...

21:00.694 --> 21:02.609
- We did.

21:02.652 --> 21:05.525
- And I thought you...
- I do.

21:05.568 --> 21:07.744
- [scoffs] So then why not see
where this goes?

21:07.788 --> 21:11.139
- [sighs] I wish I could,
I really do, but I can't.

21:11.182 --> 21:12.749
- Because?

21:12.793 --> 21:14.708
- Because...

21:14.751 --> 21:16.710
- Hey, I'm a big girl.
I can take it.

21:16.753 --> 21:18.146
What?

21:20.627 --> 21:23.717
- Because you're not black.

21:23.760 --> 21:25.414
[gate buzzes]

21:27.895 --> 21:29.418
- Gate!

21:30.114 --> 21:31.507
- Hands.
Thank you.

21:31.551 --> 21:33.117
Hands, hands.
Thank you.

21:33.161 --> 21:34.902
Hands, hands...

21:34.945 --> 21:37.383
Jemma.

21:37.426 --> 21:39.080
You know pens and pencils
aren't allowed outside

21:39.123 --> 21:40.690
the classroom.
- The pen's attached

21:40.734 --> 21:41.952
to my journal.
- Okay.

21:41.996 --> 21:43.606
You'll have to give me
the journal, then.

21:43.650 --> 21:45.086
- No.
- You'll get it back

21:45.129 --> 21:46.914
in the morning.

21:46.957 --> 21:49.960
- It's mine.
- Jemma, give me the journal.

21:50.004 --> 21:51.484
Jemma, don't do this.

21:51.527 --> 21:52.746
[echoing]
Jemma...

21:52.789 --> 21:54.617
please...
- But it's mine!

21:54.661 --> 21:56.402
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.
- [screaming]

21:56.445 --> 21:58.578
[all shouting]

21:58.621 --> 22:01.145
[dark music]

22:03.626 --> 22:05.933
- Dr. Frome told me
that he gave you that journal

22:05.976 --> 22:08.152
when you were ten.

22:10.154 --> 22:12.983
- It's mine.
- Hmm.

22:13.027 --> 22:15.943
Can I ask why you pushed...
- It's the only thing

22:15.986 --> 22:18.511
that's mine.

22:23.646 --> 22:25.779
- Jemma...

22:25.822 --> 22:27.955
what do you want to happen?

22:27.998 --> 22:30.958
[somber music]

22:31.001 --> 22:32.786
Jemma.

22:32.829 --> 22:34.744
♪

22:34.788 --> 22:36.964
What do you want to happen?

22:37.007 --> 22:39.270
♪

22:39.314 --> 22:42.143
- Nobody's ever...

22:42.186 --> 22:44.014
asked me that...

22:44.058 --> 22:45.842
before.

22:45.886 --> 22:48.932
♪

22:48.976 --> 22:50.717
- Do you want to stay here,
Jemma?

22:50.760 --> 22:53.763
Do you want to stay
at New Amsterdam?

22:53.807 --> 22:56.636
♪

22:56.679 --> 22:58.289
[clears throat]

22:58.333 --> 23:00.117
♪

23:00.161 --> 23:02.468
Well, would you like me
to get you placed

23:02.511 --> 23:04.861
in a new home
by Social Services?

23:04.905 --> 23:06.297
♪

23:06.341 --> 23:07.690
- Just decide for me.

23:07.734 --> 23:09.257
I mean, you're gonna
do it anyway.

23:09.300 --> 23:11.259
- That's--that's not true.
That--no.

23:11.302 --> 23:12.913
Hey, Jemma.

23:12.956 --> 23:14.915
- Keep it.

23:14.958 --> 23:17.221
Like, what's the point?

23:17.265 --> 23:22.749
♪

23:22.792 --> 23:24.533
[slams book]

23:24.577 --> 23:26.143
♪

23:26.187 --> 23:27.884
- Return them to baseline
and put them through

23:27.928 --> 23:30.060
the system.

23:30.104 --> 23:31.845
That's my job.

23:31.888 --> 23:33.673
- Look...

23:33.716 --> 23:36.676
if you can't help Jemma
as a doctor...

23:36.719 --> 23:39.113
then just help her
as a human being.

23:39.156 --> 23:41.158
- Am I allowed to do that?

23:41.202 --> 23:43.247
- You are now.

23:43.291 --> 23:47.730
♪

23:47.774 --> 23:50.733
[upbeat music]

23:50.777 --> 23:52.822
♪

23:52.866 --> 23:54.520
- Dr. Goodwin?

23:54.563 --> 23:57.087
- How can I help?
- Dr. Kapoor's patient in 1208,

23:57.131 --> 23:58.349
you wanted to be kept
in the loop?

23:58.393 --> 24:00.177
- Yes, thank you.
How's she doing?

24:00.221 --> 24:03.224
- I think Dr. Kapoor
is going to kill her.

24:03.267 --> 24:04.878
- Max.

24:04.921 --> 24:06.967
This is Detective Rose
from NYPD

24:07.010 --> 24:09.273
and Agent Bratton from the FBI.
- The CDC alerted us

24:09.317 --> 24:10.971
to your patient with Ebola.

24:11.014 --> 24:12.668
- Uh, we're still waiting
on the test results.

24:12.712 --> 24:14.235
I'll be with you
in five minutes.

24:14.278 --> 24:16.890
- The NSA just intercepted
a video made by ISIS.

24:16.933 --> 24:19.066
They claim they sent one
of their followers from Liberia

24:19.109 --> 24:20.807
to New York City...

24:20.850 --> 24:22.896
infected with the Ebola virus.

24:22.939 --> 24:25.768
Your patient is now
a terror suspect.

24:25.812 --> 24:28.118
[dramatic music]

24:29.772 --> 24:31.252
- A man came to my village.

24:31.295 --> 24:32.862
- What was his name?

24:32.906 --> 24:34.081
- Ayaan

24:34.124 --> 24:35.735
- Last name?

24:35.778 --> 24:37.563
- I don't know.

24:37.606 --> 24:39.173
He was showing off money

24:39.216 --> 24:41.001
he made in America

24:41.044 --> 24:43.699
from selling kufi hats
and dashikis

24:43.743 --> 24:45.266
In Times Square.

24:45.309 --> 24:47.268
He offered to give me clothes
to sell

24:47.311 --> 24:49.705
and a plane ticket
if I give him half

24:49.749 --> 24:52.229
of what I make.
- And you believed him.

24:52.273 --> 24:54.057
- Yes...

24:54.101 --> 24:57.321
He took me to doctor
for traveler's vaccination.

24:57.365 --> 24:59.585
- Alain, where did Ayaan
want you to go

24:59.628 --> 25:01.412
when you got to America?

25:01.456 --> 25:04.372
- Youth hostel in Times Square.

25:04.415 --> 25:06.156
- Then why did you come here?

25:06.200 --> 25:08.071
- This is the only hospital

25:08.115 --> 25:10.639
in America I heard of.

25:16.210 --> 25:18.125
[panel beeps]
- He's not a terrorist.

25:18.168 --> 25:19.735
- We'll gather the evidence.

25:19.779 --> 25:21.694
- If he was a terrorist,
he would have gone

25:21.737 --> 25:23.609
to Times Square, where he could
have infected the entire city,

25:23.652 --> 25:25.872
but he didn't.
He came here to get better.

25:25.915 --> 25:27.917
He was clearly tricked
into getting something

25:27.961 --> 25:29.832
injected into his bloodstream.
You see that, right?

25:29.876 --> 25:32.182
- Dr. Goodwin...
- Just please promise me

25:32.226 --> 25:34.968
you will look into his story.

25:35.011 --> 25:37.840
- I'll look into it.

25:37.884 --> 25:40.887
- What does that even mean?
"Because I'm not black."

25:40.930 --> 25:42.410
- Patient is stable,
in case you were wondering.

25:42.453 --> 25:43.803
- Oh, good.

25:43.846 --> 25:45.892
So, are you gonna
answer my question?

25:45.935 --> 25:47.328
- [sighs]

25:47.371 --> 25:49.809
I'm 35 years old.
I want to get married,

25:49.852 --> 25:51.898
I wanna have kids,
and I want them to be black.

25:51.941 --> 25:53.682
- [laughs]
You know you can't just

25:53.726 --> 25:55.641
order that off a menu, right?
- Well, yeah,

25:55.684 --> 25:57.164
but I also know I'm not gonna
meet anyone

25:57.207 --> 25:59.340
if you and I are...
- Getting our swirl on?

25:59.383 --> 26:00.950
- [sighs]
Look, I don't expect you

26:00.994 --> 26:02.909
to understand.
- I'm sorry, okay?

26:02.952 --> 26:05.433
I want to, I do.
- I have this plan

26:05.476 --> 26:07.478
for how I want my life
to look, all right?

26:07.522 --> 26:09.002
I have for a long time,
and that plan's

26:09.045 --> 26:10.873
important to me.
- So what part of the plan

26:10.917 --> 26:12.483
was taking me back
to your place and...

26:12.527 --> 26:15.051
- Whoa, whoa, hey.
Look, okay.

26:15.095 --> 26:16.357
It wasn't, all right?

26:16.400 --> 26:19.360
But when I was with you I...

26:19.403 --> 26:21.884
forgot I had a plan.
- No, sorry.

26:21.928 --> 26:24.757
I still don't understand.

26:24.800 --> 26:26.672
- Well, I guess
that's the point, right?

26:26.715 --> 26:29.065
You can't.
You can't understand

26:29.109 --> 26:30.806
how confusing it was
growing up watching

26:30.850 --> 26:32.852
every black athlete have
a white girl on his arm.

26:32.895 --> 26:34.680
Or how betrayed
black women felt--

26:34.723 --> 26:36.377
my mom, my sisters--
watching it happen

26:36.420 --> 26:38.292
time and again.
- I get it.

26:38.335 --> 26:39.989
You're just taking one
for the team.

26:40.033 --> 26:41.469
- I love black women.

26:41.512 --> 26:43.036
- So do I.

26:43.079 --> 26:45.778
But I don't see one
asking you out for a drink.

26:45.821 --> 26:48.781
[funky percussion music]

26:48.824 --> 26:53.307
♪

26:53.350 --> 26:55.701
- I asked you to keep me
in the loop on 1208.

26:55.744 --> 26:57.180
- I needed to conduct
thorough patient...

26:57.224 --> 26:59.008
- I'm taking the patient
out of your service.

26:59.052 --> 27:00.531
- Because?
- Because you should have made

27:00.575 --> 27:02.229
a presumptive diagnosis.
Because you should have

27:02.272 --> 27:04.361
aggressively treated
the Parkinson's.

27:04.405 --> 27:06.799
- Except she doesn't have
Parkinson's.

27:08.452 --> 27:09.976
PET scan.

27:10.019 --> 27:11.412
Small black flecks
over her heart.

27:11.455 --> 27:13.370
- Artifacts.

27:13.414 --> 27:15.808
- Look closer.

27:15.851 --> 27:17.810
Two years ago, Patricia
was misdiagnosed

27:17.853 --> 27:19.855
with depression.
She was prescribed Haloperidol,

27:19.899 --> 27:21.422
which caused stiffness...
- Right.

27:21.465 --> 27:23.076
- As the result,
she was misdiagnosed

27:23.119 --> 27:25.252
with Parkinson
and prescribed Levodopa,

27:25.295 --> 27:27.515
which made it impossible
for her to sleep.

27:27.558 --> 27:29.517
So she was prescribed
Hydroxyzine.

27:29.560 --> 27:31.998
That toxic combination caused
both cardiac arrest

27:32.041 --> 27:33.434
and rigidity.

27:33.477 --> 27:35.305
But this whole time,
her true symptom

27:35.349 --> 27:37.220
was her immune system
fighting a tumor

27:37.264 --> 27:39.309
that nobody could see.

27:39.353 --> 27:41.050
Small black flecks.

27:41.094 --> 27:42.486
[solemn music]

27:42.530 --> 27:45.272
- Malignant thymoma.
- Yeah.

27:45.315 --> 27:47.100
If I continued treated her
for Parkinson's,

27:47.143 --> 27:50.190
she would have another
cardiac arrest and died.

27:50.233 --> 27:51.495
♪

27:51.539 --> 27:53.933
By taking my time--
by slowing down--

27:53.976 --> 27:56.239
I bought her another year.

27:56.283 --> 27:57.980
Maybe two.

27:58.024 --> 28:00.200
♪

28:00.243 --> 28:02.332
- How can I help?

28:02.376 --> 28:04.291
♪

28:04.334 --> 28:06.032
- When she wakes up,

28:06.075 --> 28:08.077
you can help me tell her...

28:08.121 --> 28:10.079
she's going to die.

28:10.123 --> 28:17.173
♪

28:17.913 --> 28:19.393
- Well, move Sugarman
to Wednesday

28:19.436 --> 28:21.438
and I'll do Hinkle via Skype
from the hotel.

28:21.482 --> 28:23.223
Just make sure I have
his updated--

28:23.266 --> 28:24.398
uh, Ron--

28:24.441 --> 28:25.921
Ron, I said JFK.

28:25.965 --> 28:27.488
Why are we back
at New Amsterdam?

28:27.531 --> 28:28.968
[cars honking]

28:29.011 --> 28:30.534
[tires squealing]

28:34.277 --> 28:36.410
- Hi.
Remember me?

28:37.846 --> 28:39.805
- You told my driver
to bring me back here?

28:39.848 --> 28:41.894
- No, I told our driver
to bring you back here

28:41.937 --> 28:43.286
because Ron works
for New Amsterdam--

28:43.330 --> 28:45.332
and so do you, remember?

28:45.375 --> 28:47.421
- If I miss my flight...
- You can keep your job.

28:47.464 --> 28:48.596
- Why do you care about me
so much?

28:48.639 --> 28:50.337
- Because you're a good doctor.

28:50.380 --> 28:52.165
Because you bring in patients
who would otherwise never go

28:52.208 --> 28:53.819
to a public hospital,
which helps pay

28:53.862 --> 28:55.472
for the patients
who can't go anywhere else.

28:55.516 --> 28:57.648
- So it's about money.
- It's about care.

28:57.692 --> 28:59.433
Which is why I can't figure out
why'd you'd rather

28:59.476 --> 29:01.391
give lectures
to semi-retired physicians

29:01.435 --> 29:04.307
than actually provide care
to patients.

29:06.962 --> 29:09.008
- I'll see you next week.
- Come back in 48 hours

29:09.051 --> 29:11.010
or don't come back at all.

29:11.053 --> 29:17.059
♪

29:27.026 --> 29:27.243
.

29:27.287 --> 29:29.463
- Blanca?
Hi.

29:29.506 --> 29:31.160
Dr. Frome from New Amsterdam.
- Hi.

29:31.204 --> 29:32.509
- Thank you so much
for meeting me.

29:32.553 --> 29:34.685
I, um--I brought you donuts.

29:34.729 --> 29:36.818
I ate one already.
I'm sorry.

29:37.688 --> 29:39.255
I actually ate two.
I don't know why I said one,

29:39.299 --> 29:40.779
that's...
[laughs]

29:40.822 --> 29:42.824
- I have to be at work soon,
so I don't...

29:42.868 --> 29:45.261
- Yeah.
No, of course.

29:46.741 --> 29:49.178
Uh, I just--
I wanted you to see this.

29:50.223 --> 29:52.051
It's, uh--it's a journal
from the patient

29:52.094 --> 29:53.748
I was telling you about--
Jemma?

29:53.792 --> 29:56.011
Normally there'd be
privacy issues but, uh,

29:56.055 --> 29:57.883
you know, this is the one thing
that Jemma kept

29:57.926 --> 29:59.798
from foster home
to foster home.

29:59.841 --> 30:01.843
and, uh, one of those homes
was actually...

30:01.887 --> 30:03.845
your mother's.

30:08.981 --> 30:11.113
Uh, C--Camilla, right?
That--that was her name?

30:11.157 --> 30:12.680
Camilla?

30:12.723 --> 30:14.160
[clears throat]
Well, Camilla was

30:14.203 --> 30:15.814
the first foster parent

30:15.857 --> 30:18.642
to really make Jemma feel safe.

30:18.686 --> 30:20.601
You know, safe to grow
and safe to--

30:20.644 --> 30:22.255
to be a kid, really.

30:22.298 --> 30:25.693
And, uh, after Camilla died,

30:25.736 --> 30:27.651
Jemma wrote pages and pages
about her in here.

30:27.695 --> 30:29.697
You can--you can read.

30:29.740 --> 30:32.743
- My mother and I
were estranged...

30:32.787 --> 30:34.833
when she died.

30:36.356 --> 30:39.881
I didn't even know
she took in foster kids.

30:39.925 --> 30:42.188
- Oh.
- I was a tough kid to raise.

30:42.231 --> 30:44.059
Stubborn, wild.

30:44.103 --> 30:45.887
Left when I was 16.
- You know,

30:45.931 --> 30:47.758
that sounds a lot like Jemma.

30:47.802 --> 30:49.586
Tough, but she's got
a big heart.

30:49.630 --> 30:51.719
- I can't be her foster parent

30:51.762 --> 30:54.069
if that's what this is about.

30:57.377 --> 30:58.900
- I--I'm sorry.
[sighs]

30:58.944 --> 31:01.903
This was a long shot,
I know that.

31:01.947 --> 31:04.863
Thank you for meeting me.
I--I really do appreciate it.

31:05.951 --> 31:08.301
[mellow music]

31:08.344 --> 31:11.608
Can I just leave this with you?

31:11.652 --> 31:13.045
You don't have
to get it back to me--

31:13.088 --> 31:14.742
I'll come back
and pick it up later--

31:14.785 --> 31:17.310
but can I just leave it
with you?

31:17.353 --> 31:19.355
- Why?
- I think that you'll see

31:19.399 --> 31:21.053
that your mother gave Jemma
all the love

31:21.096 --> 31:23.229
that she couldn't give to you.

31:23.272 --> 31:24.970
♪

31:25.013 --> 31:27.233
That love didn't go to waste.

31:27.276 --> 31:34.327
♪

31:36.155 --> 31:38.679
- I don't understand...

31:38.722 --> 31:41.334
- I never had Parkinson's?

31:41.377 --> 31:43.031
♪

31:43.075 --> 31:44.815
And--and the depression?

31:44.859 --> 31:47.601
Hormones from your tumor.

31:47.644 --> 31:49.255
They triggered
your immune system

31:49.298 --> 31:52.214
and set off a cascade
of symptoms.

31:52.258 --> 31:53.955
Patricia...

31:53.999 --> 31:57.132
your mind is strong
and resilient.

31:57.176 --> 32:00.701
I'm sorry you were led
to believe otherwise.

32:00.744 --> 32:02.877
- Mrs. Martín...

32:02.921 --> 32:04.966
you could stay here...

32:05.010 --> 32:08.100
but in this case the treatment
is worse than the disease.

32:08.143 --> 32:09.971
- [sniffles]

32:10.015 --> 32:12.669
- And with so little time...

32:12.713 --> 32:15.281
maybe there's someplace else
you'd rather be.

32:15.324 --> 32:17.022
[somber music]

32:17.065 --> 32:18.893
- No, we stay here.

32:18.937 --> 32:20.634
We fight.
She get better.

32:20.677 --> 32:22.331
- No.

32:22.375 --> 32:24.029
I want to go home.

32:24.072 --> 32:25.987
[sobs]
To see my parents,

32:26.031 --> 32:28.207
my girls.

32:28.250 --> 32:31.123
I haven't seen them
in 11 years.

32:31.166 --> 32:33.342
- That's a wonderful idea.

32:33.386 --> 32:35.997
- We can't go home.

32:36.041 --> 32:37.825
Home is Chiapas.

32:37.868 --> 32:40.306
We crossed the border
without papers.

32:40.349 --> 32:42.177
We cross back...

32:42.221 --> 32:45.267
we will be arrested.
- I have to go home.

32:45.311 --> 32:52.144
♪

32:52.187 --> 32:54.146
[indistinct chatter]

32:54.189 --> 32:56.017
♪

32:56.061 --> 32:57.671
- Mister Ambassador?

32:57.714 --> 32:59.803
- Yes.
- Can I ask a favor?

32:59.847 --> 33:01.980
- Of course.
You need some Yankees tickets?

33:02.023 --> 33:04.330
- I need you to repatriate
two of your citizens.

33:04.373 --> 33:05.766
♪

33:05.809 --> 33:08.029
[alarm beeping]

33:08.073 --> 33:09.161
[dramatic music]

33:09.204 --> 33:11.032
- [coughing]

33:11.076 --> 33:12.860
- Hemoptysis!
He's crashing!

33:12.903 --> 33:14.731
♪

33:14.775 --> 33:16.385
Hey, can someone help me
in my suit?

33:16.429 --> 33:17.865
♪

33:17.908 --> 33:20.085
Alain!
Alain, you need to grab

33:20.128 --> 33:22.130
the oxygen mask!

33:22.174 --> 33:23.784
Alain!

33:23.827 --> 33:26.395
Alain, it is right above you.

33:26.439 --> 33:28.006
- [coughing]

33:28.049 --> 33:29.877
[gasping]

33:29.920 --> 33:32.053
♪

33:32.097 --> 33:34.273
- Helmet, now!
- [coughing, gasping]

33:34.316 --> 33:37.232
♪

33:37.276 --> 33:38.407
[alarm wailing]

33:38.451 --> 33:40.409
- Forget it.

33:40.453 --> 33:41.976
♪

33:42.020 --> 33:43.369
I'm going in.

33:43.412 --> 33:45.327
- Dr. Bloom, wait.

33:45.371 --> 33:52.421
♪

33:55.859 --> 33:57.209
Okay.

33:57.252 --> 34:00.386
♪

34:00.429 --> 34:01.778
- Bloom!

34:01.822 --> 34:03.389
Get out of there, now!

34:03.432 --> 34:06.087
- It's too late!
I'm already in!

34:06.131 --> 34:08.176
There's too much blood,
I can't see anything.

34:08.220 --> 34:12.485
♪

34:12.528 --> 34:14.400
[alarm beeping]

34:14.443 --> 34:16.358
♪

34:16.402 --> 34:18.404
- Heart rate is dropping.
He needs adrenaline.

34:18.447 --> 34:20.536
- I can't stop bagging.
- Adrenaline first,

34:20.580 --> 34:22.103
oxygen after, okay?

34:22.147 --> 34:23.496
Go.

34:23.539 --> 34:30.807
♪

34:32.592 --> 34:35.247
Okay, now push 10 ml's,
open wide.

34:35.290 --> 34:37.510
- But that's too much.
- Not for this kind of virus.

34:37.553 --> 34:39.773
- Max, it'll send
his heart rate too high.

34:39.816 --> 34:42.036
- Push 10 hard and fast,
right now.

34:42.080 --> 34:49.087
♪

34:53.134 --> 34:56.137
[monitor beeping]

34:59.488 --> 35:01.099
- Lauren...

35:01.142 --> 35:02.448
- I know what you're gonna say.
That was--

35:02.491 --> 35:05.015
that was stupid.
I violated the protocol.

35:05.059 --> 35:06.234
[suspenseful music]

35:06.278 --> 35:08.062
- [clears throat]
Lauren...

35:08.106 --> 35:09.150
♪

35:09.194 --> 35:10.456
Your glove.

35:10.499 --> 35:14.982
♪

35:15.025 --> 35:16.984
[phone vibrating]

35:17.027 --> 35:18.333
♪

35:18.377 --> 35:20.161
- Doctor.

35:20.205 --> 35:23.164
♪

35:23.208 --> 35:25.123
- Sorry, I can't talk
right now.

35:25.166 --> 35:27.299
- There's something wrong
with the baby.

35:27.342 --> 35:29.170
[weeping]
Oh, my God.

35:29.214 --> 35:32.260
♪

35:35.133 --> 35:35.307
.

35:35.350 --> 35:37.831
- She's bleeding.
- I need a trans-abdominal

35:37.874 --> 35:39.180
ultrasound, mag sulfate--
4 grams.

35:39.224 --> 35:40.921
- BP 160 over 110.
- How we doing

35:40.964 --> 35:42.444
with that second...
- Draw a chem 24

35:42.488 --> 35:44.185
and coag panel.
Let's get the fetal monitor on.

35:44.229 --> 35:46.274
- How can I help?
- By getting out of the way.

35:46.318 --> 35:48.929
- This is my wife.
- And she needs you.

35:48.972 --> 35:50.409
- Oh, God.
- Off the o2.

35:50.452 --> 35:52.150
[all chattering]

35:52.193 --> 35:53.325
all: One, two, three.

35:53.368 --> 35:55.283
- [gasps]
- Baby's in distress.

35:55.327 --> 35:57.111
- No...
- You're okay, I'm right here.

35:57.155 --> 35:59.113
I'm with you.
- Push 4 mag sulfate.

35:59.157 --> 36:00.506
- Max.
- No, no, just focus on me.

36:00.549 --> 36:02.377
I'm right here.
- [heavy breathing]

36:02.421 --> 36:04.074
- Ultrasound's up.

36:04.118 --> 36:06.512
[suspenseful music]

36:06.555 --> 36:08.470
She's complete previa.

36:08.514 --> 36:10.255
- What's that?
- It means your placenta

36:10.298 --> 36:11.821
is obstructing your cervix.
There's nowhere

36:11.865 --> 36:13.301
for the baby to go.

36:13.345 --> 36:15.956
- Corticosteroids
and a unit of O-negative,

36:15.999 --> 36:17.305
and type and cross.

36:17.349 --> 36:20.308
- This is because of me.
- You did nothing wrong.

36:20.352 --> 36:23.093
- It's my fault.
- Georgia, if we can't control

36:23.137 --> 36:24.399
the bleeding,
we're going to need to do

36:24.443 --> 36:26.488
an emergency caesarean,
understand?

36:26.532 --> 36:28.621
- The baby is not ready.
She's not ready.

36:28.664 --> 36:30.231
- We're not gonna have
a choice.

36:30.275 --> 36:32.320
- Is she still bleeding?
- Bleeding's slowed down.

36:32.364 --> 36:34.017
- I still want a transfusion,

36:34.061 --> 36:35.976
and someone tell me
baby's heart rate?

36:36.019 --> 36:38.413
- I can't find it.
- What?

36:38.457 --> 36:41.199
- I can't find
the baby's heart beat.

36:41.242 --> 36:45.551
♪

36:45.594 --> 36:47.509
- Suzanne?

36:47.553 --> 36:49.294
- Come on.
- It's okay.

36:49.337 --> 36:52.079
- Suzanne...

36:52.122 --> 36:53.341
- Where are you?

36:53.385 --> 36:58.520
♪

36:58.564 --> 36:59.521
[thrumming]
There you are, baby girl.

36:59.565 --> 37:01.262
- Oh, God.

37:01.306 --> 37:03.133
[inhales shakily]
[thrumming continues]

37:03.177 --> 37:05.310
[laughing, sobbing]

37:05.353 --> 37:06.876
[Coldplay's "Fix You"]

37:06.920 --> 37:08.661
- Looking good.

37:08.704 --> 37:10.967
- It's okay.
- [laughs]

37:11.011 --> 37:12.969
♪

37:13.013 --> 37:14.971
- Does baby have a name yet?

37:15.015 --> 37:19.933
♪

37:19.976 --> 37:21.674
- Luna.

37:21.717 --> 37:26.592
- ♪ When you try your best
but you don't succeed ♪

37:26.635 --> 37:28.246
♪

37:28.289 --> 37:30.465
♪ When you get what you want

37:30.509 --> 37:32.946
♪ But not what you need

37:32.989 --> 37:34.991
♪

37:35.035 --> 37:37.167
♪ When you feel so tired

37:37.211 --> 37:39.344
♪ But you can't sleep

37:39.387 --> 37:40.475
♪

37:40.519 --> 37:43.522
♪ Stuck in reverse...

37:43.565 --> 37:45.393
- Dr. Frome?

37:45.437 --> 37:48.135
♪

37:48.178 --> 37:50.442
- ♪ When the tears
come streaming ♪

37:50.485 --> 37:53.140
♪ Down your face

37:53.183 --> 37:54.968
♪

37:55.011 --> 37:57.057
♪ When you lose something

37:57.100 --> 37:59.102
♪ You can't replace

37:59.146 --> 38:00.408
♪

38:00.452 --> 38:02.236
[no audible dialogue]

38:02.280 --> 38:03.933
♪

38:03.977 --> 38:10.331
♪ Lights will guide you home

38:10.375 --> 38:17.077
♪ And ignite your bones

38:17.120 --> 38:19.645
♪ And I will try

38:19.688 --> 38:21.299
♪

38:21.342 --> 38:23.126
♪ To fix you

38:23.170 --> 38:27.348
♪

38:27.392 --> 38:29.089
- Oh...
- [gasps, sobs]

38:29.132 --> 38:30.569
- [sobbing]
Mommy.

38:30.612 --> 38:32.658
- ♪ When the tears
come streaming ♪

38:32.701 --> 38:35.313
[both crying]
♪ Down your face

38:35.356 --> 38:36.662
♪

38:36.705 --> 38:39.099
♪ When you lose something

38:39.142 --> 38:41.188
[all weeping]
- Mija...

38:41.231 --> 38:45.323
♪

38:45.366 --> 38:52.068
- ♪ Lights will guide
you home ♪

38:52.112 --> 38:58.640
♪ And ignite your bones

38:58.684 --> 39:00.773
♪ And I will try

39:00.816 --> 39:02.470
♪

39:02.514 --> 39:04.646
♪ To fix you

39:04.690 --> 39:11.740
♪

39:16.223 --> 39:18.312
- Alaim, that shot
they gave you in Liberia--

39:18.356 --> 39:20.575
they might have thought
it was Ebola,

39:20.619 --> 39:22.403
but it wasn't.

39:22.447 --> 39:25.667
It was the Lassa virus,
which is just as deadly...

39:25.711 --> 39:28.714
except, as Dr. Bloom
can tell you,

39:28.757 --> 39:30.498
the Lassa virus can be treated

39:30.542 --> 39:32.587
with antiviral medication,

39:32.631 --> 39:34.676
which we gave you.

39:34.720 --> 39:38.201
♪

39:38.245 --> 39:41.335
[all clapping]
- ♪ Tears stream

39:41.379 --> 39:44.556
♪ Down your face

39:44.599 --> 39:47.297
♪ When you lose something

39:47.341 --> 39:50.257
- Nice job, Dr. Bloom.
- ♪ You cannot replace...

39:50.300 --> 39:52.390
- You wanna go
and grab a drink?

39:52.433 --> 39:54.609
- Seriously?
Now?

39:54.653 --> 39:57.090
- I'm talking about
a nice glass of scotch.

39:57.133 --> 39:58.831
What are you talking about?

39:58.874 --> 40:01.573
- Yeah.
Yeah, I could use a drink.

40:01.616 --> 40:05.403
♪

40:05.446 --> 40:11.670
- ♪ Lights will guide
you home ♪

40:11.713 --> 40:15.238
♪ And I will try
[knocking on door]

40:15.282 --> 40:16.544
- Dr. Sharpe.
- ♪ To fix you

40:16.588 --> 40:18.241
- I hope I'm not interrupting.

40:18.285 --> 40:20.635
- No, no, I was just, um...

40:22.463 --> 40:24.465
my sister was here...

40:24.509 --> 40:27.642
in this room a long time ago
and I was just, uh...

40:28.904 --> 40:31.167
Introducing her to someone.

40:33.169 --> 40:34.562
- I, um...

40:34.606 --> 40:36.825
I saw the Farmer's Market.

40:36.869 --> 40:38.305
- Oh, yeah?
Did you buy anything?

40:38.348 --> 40:40.438
- Couldn't.
